solution.p:
When there are two terms in the denominator, we multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, in this case ~\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{x}.  
    \dfrac{x\blert{(\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{x})}}{(\sqrt{2}+\sqrt{x})\blert{(\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{x})}}=\dfrac{x({\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{x})}}{2-x} 
We have used the formula for the differnce of two squares, ~(a+b)(a-b)=a^2-b^2,~ to simplify ~(\sqrt{2}+\sqrt{x})(\sqrt{2}-\sqrt{x})~ to ~2-x~.

Use the formula ~(a-b)^2=a^2-2ab+b^2~ with ~a=\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}~ and ~b=\dfrac{1}{2}.~
    (a-b)^2 \amp = a^2-2ab+b^2
        \left(\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}-\dfrac{1}{2}\right)^2 \amp = \left(\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2-2\left(\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)\left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right)+\left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right)^2
         \amp = \dfrac{-3}{4}-\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}+\dfrac{1}{4}
         \amp = \dfrac{-1}{2}-\dfrac{i\sqrt{3}}{2}
